<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-071-047 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 214 331</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  Sept 1991 v28 n9 p26(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Warfare in the information age. (Gulf legacy/high-techwarfare)(1991 Persian Gulf War)(includes related article oncomputerized communications) (Cover Story)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Adam, John A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The sprawling and complex high tech electronic information systemused by the US in the 1991 Persian Gulf War, called command,control, communications, computers and intelligence (C to thepower of four-I), enabled the West to dominate air and landbattles.andP;  The western allies used computers in airplanes andtanks, digital databases instead of maps, software andmicrocomputers for a command and control network, and satellitedishes and faxes for access to real-time information.andP;  Computermodels analyzed Iraq's weaknesses.andP;  C4-I enabled precisionattacks, with a minute .041 percent loss rate on sorties and atarget success rate of 82 to 86 percent.andP;  Though it weakenedIraq's defense, C4-I wasn't infallible.andP;  The US misjudged the sizeof the Iraqi force, couldn't detect mobile Scud launchers andsystems couldn't identify friend from foe in battle.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MilitaryWeaponsMiddle EastInformation SystemsIraqStrategic PlanningCommunications TechnologyCommand and Control SystemsData AnalysisHigh Technology.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographmapchart.andO;Caption:   The first 24 hours. (map)Busting Scuds with an F-15E. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>